<section label="why-exponentials-solve-lhcc"><title> Why Exponentials Solve LHCC Equations </title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
		Now that we can identify LHCC equations, it’s time to ask a deeper question: what kinds of functions satisfy these equations? As it turns out, exponential functions are not just one possible answer—they are the natural solution.
		</p>
		
		<p>
		In this section, we’ll explore what makes exponentials so special. You’ll see why other functions fail to work, why exponentials succeed, and how this leads us to a powerful tool called the <em>characteristic equation</em>.
		</p>
	</introduction>

<paragraphs xml:id="motivating-exponentials">
    <title> Motivating the Exponential Solution </title>

	<exercise>
		<title> Recall From Your Past </title>
		<task>
			<title> ⏪ Functions that are equal to their own derivatives </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the only function that is equal to its own derivative?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\quad y = e^{x} </m></statement>
					<feedback>Correct!<m>\frac{d}{dx}[e^{x}] = e^{x}</m></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad y = \tan x </m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. <m>\frac{d}{dx}[\tan x] = \sec^2 x</m>, not <m>\tan x</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad y = x^2 </m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. <m>\frac{d}{dx}[x^2] = 2x</m>, not <m>x^2</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad y = \ln x </m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. <m>\frac{d}{dx}[\ln x] = \frac{1}{x}</m>, not <m>\ln x</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task>
			<title> ⏪ Like Terms </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Terms are called <term>like-terms</term> if they have identical variable parts. That is, they differ only by a coefficient. Like-terms can be combined via addition and subtraction. 
				</p>
				<p>
					For example, the <m>5e^{-3x}</m> and <m>4e^{-3x}</m> are like terms, but <m>5e^{-3x}</m> and <m>2e^{7x}</m> are not. Additionally, like terms can be combined/simplified as follows:
					<md>
						<mrow> \underline{3x^2} + 2e^{7x} + \underline{\underline{5e^{-3x}}} \amp - 2 + \underline{7x^2} - \underline{\underline{4e^{-3x}}}</mrow>
						<mrow> \downarrow \quad \amp \text{simplified} </mrow>
						<mrow> \underline{10x^2} + 2e^{7x} \amp + \underline{\underline{e^{-3x}}} - 2 </mrow>
					</md>.
				</p>
				<p>
					Which of the following are like-terms with <m>\cos(3x)</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\quad 2\cos(3x) </m></statement>
					<feedback>Correct! <m>2\cos(3x)</m> is a like-term with <m>\cos(3x)</m> and <m>2\cos(3x) + \cos(3x) = 3\cos(3x)</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\quad -7\cos(3x) </m></statement>
					<feedback>Correct! <m>-7\cos(3x)</m> is a like-term with <m>\cos(3x)</m> and <m>-7\cos(3x) + \cos(3x) = -6\cos(3x)</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad 3\sin(3x) </m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. <m>3\sin(3x)</m> is not a like-term with <m>\cos(3x)</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad 4\cos(2x) </m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. <m>4\cos(2x)</m> is not a like-term with <m>\cos(3x)</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad 3x </m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. <m>3x</m> is not a like-term with <m>\cos(3x)</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
			
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task>
			<title> ⏪ Functions that are like terms with their own derivatives </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which of the following functions are like-terms with their own derivatives?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\quad y = e^{10x} </m></statement>
					<feedback>Correct!<m>\frac{d}{dx}[e^{10x}] = 10e^{x}\ \Rightarrow\ e^{10x}</m> &amp; <m>10e^{10x}</m> ARE like terms.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad y = \sin (4x) </m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. <m>\frac{d}{dx}[\sin (4x)] = 4\cos (4x)\ \Rightarrow\ \sin(4x)</m> &amp; <m>4\cos (4x)</m> ARE NOT like terms.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad y = x^4 </m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. <m>\frac{d}{dx}[x^4] = 4x^3\ \Rightarrow\ x^4</m> &amp; <m>4x^3</m> ARE NOT like terms.</feedback> 
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad y = x^{-1} </m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. <m>\frac{d}{dx}[x^{-1}] = -x^{-2}\ \Rightarrow\ x^{-1}</m> &amp; <m>-x^{-2}</m> ARE NOT like terms.</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>
	</exercise>

	<p>
		Consider the very simple linear homogeneous constant coefficient differential equation:
		<me>y' - 2y = 0</me>.
	</p>

	<p>
		For the moment, forget that it is a differential equation and imagine that it is just two functions that simplify to zero after subtraction. That is, they cancelled out with each other. Algebra tells you that only <term>like-terms</term> simplify via subtraction.<fn>For example, <m>5x - 3x - 2x = 0</m> since all three are like-terms. However, <m>5x - 3x^2 - 2y</m> does not simplify at all since none are like-terms.</fn>
	</p>

	<p>
		Logically, if <m>y</m> is the solution, then this equation says <m>y</m> and <m>y'</m> must be like-terms since they subtract to zero. This leads to the next big question:  
	</p>

	<sidebyside margins="20% 20%">
		<p><q>What function is a like-term with its derivative?</q></p>
	</sidebyside>

	<p>
      	You may recall from calculus that the derivative of an exponential function is another exponential function. For example, if <m>y=e^{3x}</m>, then <m>y'=3e^{3x}</m>, which are like-terms. This unique property makes exponentials ideal candidates for solutions.
    </p>

	<p>
		To illustrate this, let’s substitute different functions into a first-order LHCC equation and see which ones cancel.
	</p>

	<sidebyside widths="28% 5% 32% 5% 30%">
		<p>
			<em>Case 1:</em> <m>\quad y = x^2</m>
			<md>
				<mrow> \left[x^2\right]' - 2 \left[x^2\right] \amp = 0 </mrow>
				<mrow> \ub{2x - 2x^2}_{\text{non like-terms}} \amp \ne 0 </mrow>
			</md>
		</p>
		<p/>
		<p>
			<em>Case 2:</em> <m>\quad y = \ln x</m>
			<md>
				<mrow> \left[\ln x\right]' - 2\left[\ln x\right] \amp = 0 </mrow>
				<mrow> \ub{\frac{1}{x} - 2\ln x}_{\text{non like-terms}} \amp \ne 0 </mrow>
			</md>
		</p>
		<p/>
		<p>
			<em>Case 3:</em> <m>\quad y = e^{2x}</m>
			<md>
				<mrow> \left[e^{2x}\right]' - 2 \left[e^{2x}\right] \amp = 0 </mrow>
				<mrow> \ub{2e^{2x} - 2e^{2x}}_{\text{like-terms}} \amp = 0 </mrow>
			</md>
		</p>
    </sidebyside>

	<p>
		Only the exponential function produces like-terms that cancel perfectly. Again, suggesting that exponential functions are ideal solutions to LHCC equations.
	</p>

	<example xml:id="lhcc-soln-example-1">
      <title> Multiple Exponential Solutions </title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Verify that <m>y = e^{4x}</m> and <m>y = e^{-x}</m> are solutions to the differential equation
        </p>
        <me>
          y'' - 3y' - 4y = 0
        </me>
        <p>
          but that <m>y = x^4</m>, <m>y = \ln x</m>, and <m>y = e^{3x}</m> are not.
        </p>
      </statement>
      			<solution>
				<p>
					First, let's check the first two exponential functions:
				</p>

				<sidebyside widths="20% 80%">
					<p>
						<me>
							y=e^{4x}:
						</me>
					</p>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> 	[e^{4x}]'' - 3\left[e^{4x}\right]' - 4\left[e^{4x}\right]	\amp = 0	</mrow>
							<mrow> 	
								\us{\large\text{like-terms simplify to }0}{\ub{
									16e^{4x} - 12e^{4x} - 4e^{4x}	
								}}
								\amp = 0	
							</mrow>
							<mrow> 	0	\amp = 0	\ \ ✅ </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<sidebyside widths="20% 80%">
					<p>
						<me>
							y=e^{-x}:
						</me>
					</p>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> 	[e^{-x}]'' - 3\left[e^{-x}\right]' - 4\left[e^{-x}\right]	\amp = 0	</mrow>
							<mrow> 	
								\us{\large\text{like-terms simplify to }0}{\ub{
									e^{-x} + 3e^{-x} - 4e^{-x}	
								}}
								\amp = 0	
							</mrow>
							<mrow> 	0	\amp = 0	\ \ ✅ </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<p>
					As you can see, the exponential functions produce like-terms that cancel out and simplify to zero.
				</p>

				<p>
					Let's see what happens when we plug in non-exponential functions:
				</p>

				<sidebyside widths="20% 80%">
					<p>
						<me>
							y=x^4:
						</me>
					</p>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> 	[x^4]'' - 3\left[x^4\right]' - 4\left[x^4\right]	\amp = 0	</mrow>
							<mrow> 	
								\us{\large\text{not like-terms, do not combine}}{\ub{
									12x^2 - 12x^3 - 4x^4	
								}}
								\amp = 0	\ \ ❌
							</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<sidebyside widths="20% 80%">
					<p>
						<me>
							y=\ln x:
						</me>
					</p>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> 	[\ln x]'' - 3\left[\ln x\right]' - 4\left[\ln x\right]	\amp = 0	</mrow>
							<mrow> 	
								\us{\large\text{not like-terms, do not combine}}{\ub{
									-x^{-2} - 3x^{-1} - 4\ln x	
								}}
								\amp = 0	\ \ ❌
							</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<p>
					In this case, the non-exponential functions produce non-like-terms that cannot be simplified and are not solutions.
				</p>

				<p>
					Finally, let's check the exponential function, <m>y = e^{3x}</m>:
				</p>

				<sidebyside widths="20% 80%">
					<p>
						<me>
							y=e^{3x}:
						</me>
					</p>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> 	[e^{3x}]'' - 3\left[e^{3x}\right]' - 4\left[e^{3x}\right]	\amp = 0	</mrow>
							<mrow> 	
								\us{\large\text{like-terms don't simplify to }0}{\ub{
									9e^{3x} - 9e^{3x} - 4e^{3x}	
								}}
								\amp = 0	
							</mrow>
							<mrow> 	- 4e^{3x}	\amp = 0	\ \ ❌ </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<p>
					In this case, we get like-terms, but the coefficients do not sum to zero and the terms do not cancel. Therefore, <m>y=e^{3x}</m> is not a solution.
				</p>
			</solution>
    </example>

      <p>
        These examples show that exponentials are the only functions that reliably produce like-terms when substituted into an LHCC equation. Even among exponentials, only those with specific exponents will satisfy a given equation. Next, we’ll introduce the characteristic equation, an algebraic tool that helps us identify exactly which exponential functions will work.
      </p>

</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs><title> The Characteristic Equation </title>

		<introduction>
			<p>
				We now know that exponential functions <m>y = e^{rx}</m> are strong candidates for solutions to LHCC equations. But how do we find which values of <m>r</m> work? The answer lies in forming a polynomial equation called the <em>characteristic equation</em>.
			</p>
		</introduction>

		<p>
			Let's try this with another simple example. Suppose
		</p>

		<me>y' - 5y = 0</me>.

		<p>
			Substituting <m>y = e^{rx}</m> gives
		</p>

		<md>
			<mrow> \left[e^{rx}\right]' - 5 e^{rx} \amp = 0 </mrow>
			<mrow> r e^{rx} - 5 e^{rx} \amp = 0 </mrow>
			<mrow> (r - 5)e^{rx} \amp = 0 </mrow>
		</md>

		<p>
			Since <m>e^{rx} \ne 0</m>, the equation reduces to
		</p>

		<me> r - 5 = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad r = 5 </me>

		<p>
			This algebraic equation, <m>r - 5 = 0</m>, is the <term>characteristic equation</term>. It tells us that <m>y = e^{5x}</m> is a solution.
		</p>

		<p>
			For higher-order equations, we follow the same substitution process. For example, for
		</p>

		<me>
			y'' - 3y' - 4y = 0.
		</me>

		<p>
			we substitute <m>y = e^{rx}</m> into <m>y</m>, <m>y'</m>, and <m>y''</m>, resulting in
		</p>

		<md>
			<mrow>	(r^2 e^{rx}) - 3 (r e^{rx}) - 4 (e^{rx})	\amp = 0	</mrow>
			<mrow>	(r^2 - 3r - 4) e^{rx}						\amp = 0	</mrow>
		</md>

		<p>
			Setting the polynomial equal to zero gives the characteristic equation:
		</p>

		<me>
			r^2 - 3r - 4 = 0.
		</me>

		<p>
			Solving this gives
		</p>

		<me>
			(r - 4)(r + 1) = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad r = 4, \quad r = -1
		</me>

		<p>
			so the general solution is
		</p>

		<me>
			y_1 = e^{4x}, \quad y_2 = e^{-x}.
		</me>
	</paragraphs>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li> 
				Since exponential functions like-terms with their derivatives, they make good candidates as solutions for LHCC equations.
			</li>
			<li> 
				Substituting <m>y = e^{rx}</m> into an LHCC equation leads to a polynomial equation in <m>r</m> called the <term>characteristic equation</term>. Solving this equation determines which exponential solutions satisfy the differential equation.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<exercise><title> Answer-the-Following </title>
		<task label="chkpt-why-exponentials-solve-lhcc-1"><title> Valid Function Choices </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which of the following functions could be a solution to the second-order LHCC equation
					<me>
						ay'' + by' + cy = 0
					</me>
					where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are constants?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = x^3 + 5x</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This polynomial could never be the solution to this equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = e^{5x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! Exponential functions satisfy LHCC equations because their derivatives remain constant multiple of the function itself.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = \ln x</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Logarithmic functions do not satisfy LHCC equations since their derivatives do not maintain the required form.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = \sqrt{x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. 
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-why-exponentials-solve-lhcc-2"><title> Exponential Function Property </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					<m> e^{rx} </m> and its derivatives are <q>like-terms</q> that can be combined with addition.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes"><statement>True</statement><feedback>Correct!</feedback></choice>
				<choice correct="no"><statement>False</statement><feedback>Incorrect.</feedback></choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-why-exponentials-solve-lhcc-3"><title> True-or-False </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The hundredth derivative of <m> e^{7x} </m> is a like-term with <m>e^{7x}</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes"><statement>True</statement><feedback>Correct!</feedback></choice>
				<choice correct="no"><statement>False</statement><feedback>Incorrect.</feedback></choice>
			</choices>
		</task>
	</exercise>

	<exercise><title> Characteristic Equations &amp; Fundamental Solutions </title>
	
		<task label="chkpt-why-exponentials-solve-lhcc-4"><title> Solutions to the Characteristic Equation </title>
			<statement correct="yes">
				<p>
					The order of an LHCC differential equation is equal to the degree of its characteristic equation
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					This is true, since the order of each derivative in the differential equation translates directly to a corresponding power of <m>r</m> in the characteristic equation.
				</p>
			</feedback>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-why-exponentials-solve-lhcc-5"><title> Identifying the Characteristic Equation </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the characteristic equation of the differential equation
					<me>
						2y'' + 5y' - y = 0
					</me>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad r^2 + 5r - 1 = 0</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Check the coefficients of the original differential equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad 2r^2 + 5r - 1 = 0</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The terms, <m>y''</m>, <m>y'</m>, and <m>y</m>, translate to <m>r^2</m>, <m>r^1</m>, and <m>r^0</m> in the characteristic equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad 2r^2 + 5r = 0</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Pay attention to the sign of the coefficient in front of <m>y'</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-why-exponentials-solve-lhcc-6"><title> Matching Equations to Solutions </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Match each differential equation to its characteristic equation.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					Good job! The characteristic equation is found by assuming <m>y = e^{rx}</m> and simplifying.
				</p>
			</feedback>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>y''' + 4y = 0</m></premise>
					<response><m>r^3 + 4 = 0</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>y'' - 3y' + 2y = 0</m></premise>
					<response><m>r^2 - 3r + 2 = 0</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>y'' - y' = 0</m></premise>
					<response><m>r^2 - r = 0</m></response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-why-exponentials-solve-lhcc-7"><title> Select the characteristic equation </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Select the characteristic equation for the first-order LHCC equation
					<me>
						4y' + 3y = 0
					</me>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad 4r + 3 = 1</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Remember, the characteristic equation should be formed by setting the equation to zero.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad 4r + 3 = 0</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The characteristic equation is found by substituting <m>y = e^{rx}</m> into the differential equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad 4r - 3 = 0</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Check the signs of the coefficients.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad 3r + 4 = 0</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Ensure you have used the correct coefficients from the original equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-why-exponentials-solve-lhcc-8"><title> Select the Fundamental Solutions </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Select all the fundamental solutions for the differential equation
					<me>
						y'' - 4y = 0
					</me>.
				</p>
